# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cast-iron
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Abraham Darby was the son of John Darby, a yeoman farmer and locksmith by trade, and his wife Ann Baylies.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] He was born at Wren's Nest in Woodsetton, Staffordshire, now part of Dudley, West Midlands.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] He was descended from nobility; his great-grandmother Jane was an illegitimate child of Edward Sutton.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Abraham's great-grandmother was a sister of the whole blood to Dud Dudley, who claimed to have smelted iron using coal as a fuel.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Unfortunately, the iron that Dudley produced was not acceptable to the charcoal ironmasters.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] However, this may have inspired his great-grandnephew Darby to perfect this novel method of smelting.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] In Birmingham in the early 1690s, Darby was apprenticed to Jonathan Freeth, a fellow Quaker and a manufacturer of brass mills for grinding malt.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Here Darby would have seen the use of coke to fuel malting ovens, not only preventing the sulphur content of coal from contaminating the resulting beer, but also avoiding its use of the scarcer charcoal as a fuel.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] The combination of these two insights was to lead to Darby's development of the coke-fuelled blast furnace in 1709.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Freeth encouraged Darby to become a highly active member in the Society of Friends, and he remained so all his life.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] In 1699, when he completed his apprenticeship, he married Mary Sergeant (1678–1718) and moved to Bristol, where he set himself up as a malt mill maker.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] There was a small community of Quakers in Bristol, and Darby soon gained a reputation for skill and enterprise.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] In 1702 Darby joined a number of fellow Quakers to form the Bristol Brass Company, with works at Baptist Mills in Bristol.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] He brought in 'Dutchmen' to operate a brass battery work, making cooking pots and other holloware under a trip hammer.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] He also developed a method for casting pots in 'greensand' moulds, previously only used for smaller castings.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] This enabled pots and cauldrons to be mass-produced and to be thinner than those made by the traditional process of casting in loam moulds.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] For this purpose, he established the Cheese Lane Foundry in 1704.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Initially he cast brass pots, but by 1705, he moved on to using iron.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] A young Welsh apprentice, John Thomas, solved the problem by using sand for the mould, with a special casting box and core.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Using this casting method Darby could cast pots of sufficient thinness and lightness.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Darby took out a patent on the new casting method in 1707, Darby's successors sold cooking pots over wide areas of England and Wales, and had a virtual monopoly in the trade.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] For this he used a reverberatory air furnace of a kind developed by Sir Clement Clerke, initially for smelting lead near Bristol, and applied by him or his son Talbot to iron founding at Vauxhall.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] In 1700, another group of Bristol Quakers (including Edward Lloyd and Charles Harford) had agreed to set up a brass works 'somewhere in England'.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] It is not clear where, but by 1712, Caleb Lloyd, Jeffrey Pinnell, Abraham Darby and his brother-in-law Thomas Harvey had brass works at Coalbrookdale.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] This is likely to be linked to an increase in shipment of 'Callumy' (Calamine) up the river Severn from 1704 and Darby's agreement in 1710 to open a copper mine at Harmer Hill in Myddle, on behalf of a 'Company of the City of Bristol'.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] However, Darby was not a partner in establishing Tern Mill, near Tern Hall (now Attingham Park) in 1709, though his partners Thomas Harvey, Lloyd and Pinnell were.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] At this point Darby decided to leave the brass company and concentrate on his iron founding pursuits.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Darby leased the furnace in September 1708, and set to work preparing to get it into blast.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] His first account book, running from 20 October 1708 to 4 January 1710 survives.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] This shows the production of 'charked' coal in January 1709 and the furnace was brought into blast on 10 January.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Darby sold 81 tons of iron goods that year.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] The furnace was used for the first time on 10 January 1709 and the blast appears to have been successful.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Darby was probably helped by the fact that the Shropshire 'clod coal' that he was using was fairly sulphur-free.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] However, experimentation with different fuels continued for some time; for example cargoes of coal were brought up the Severn from Bristol and Neath.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Some of the molten iron from the blast was run into pigs and sent down the Severn for use in Bristol foundries, but much of it was used to cast pots and other cast iron goods.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] The reasons why the iron produced by Darby was not used in forges to make wrought iron have been much debated.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] The reason may be partly that his pig iron was better for castings than charcoal pig iron, but the presence of silicon as an impurity made it an unattractive feedstock for finery forges.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] However recent work has thrown doubt on this explanation, which is based on data from the 1720s when the Coalbrookdale Company operated a forge: the forge could hardly even make a profit with charcoal pit iron.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] The business was partly financed by a loan from Thomas Goldney II of Bristol and by Graffin Prankard and James Peters becoming partners.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Later John Chamberlayne became a partner, and Darby's brother-in-law Thomas Baylies a manager.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] In 1712, Darby offered to instruct William Rawlinson, a fellow Quaker and ironmaster, in the techniques of smelting with coke.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Apparently, Rawlinson, the founder of the Backbarrow Iron Company in Furness, did not take up the offer.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] In 1714, Darby and his partners renewed their lease (effective from 1717) and then built a second blast furnace.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] This was slightly more productive in the 1720s than the Old Blast Furnace.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] It is not clear when this furnace began production but it was certainly in use by 1718.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] The company also secured Vale Royal Furnace in central Cheshire, but this did not come into their possession before Abraham Darby's death.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Afterward, it was taken over by Thomas Baylies with other partners.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] The Company embarked on a similar venture at Dolgûn, near Dolgellau, where John Kelsall was appointed as clerk, but it is probable that the furnace there was not finished until after Darby died, when his widow and the other partners sold off their lease.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] After 18 months' illness, Abraham Darby died on 5 May 1717, at his home, Madeley Court, Madeley, Shropshire, aged 40.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] He had built a house for himself in Coalbrookdale but did not live to occupy it.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] He was buried in the Quaker burial-ground at Broseley, Shropshire.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Darby's death left the affairs of the business in a mess.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] His own shares were mortgaged to Thomas Goldney, who then exchanged the debt for eight shares (of 16) in the business.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Richard Ford, who married Abraham's daughter Mary, had two shares and became manager, but on the widow's death Thomas Baylies took out letters of administration as a creditor and sought to sell the works.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Darby's eldest son, Abraham Darby II, was only six years old and his two brothers younger still.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Accordingly, their uncle Joshua Sergeant bought back some of the shares on behalf of the Darby children.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] The children were sent away to school, and Abraham II began assisting in the management of the works in 1728 and he was awarded four shares in the company in 1732.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Abraham Darby made an important step towards the Industrial Revolution.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] His method of casting pots in sand provided his successors with a viable business that operated for over two centuries.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Smelting iron with coke ultimately released the iron industry from the limitation imposed by the preliminary step of "charcoal burning" where trees were first cut and burned to make charcoal.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] It also shifted the fuel used for making steel from renewable wood, to a fossil fuel, and so helped preserve native woodland.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Coke-smelted cast iron went into steam engines, bridges, and many of the inventions of the 19th century.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] Coke smelting made possible the great quantities of iron produced which drove the Industrial Revolution.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-i] The Abraham Darby room at Friends House, London, UK is named after him.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] Abraham Darby was born in Coalbrookdale, Shropshire, in 1750, the eldest son of Abraham Darby the Younger (1711–1763) by his second wife, Abiah Maude, and educated at a school in Worcester kept by a Quaker named James Fell.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] At age thirteen, Darby inherited his father's shares in the family iron-making businesses in the Severn Valley, and in 1768, aged eighteen, he took over the management of the Coalbrookdale ironworks.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] He took various measures to improve the conditions of his work force.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] In times of food shortage he bought up farms to grow food for his workers, he built housing for them, and he offered higher wages than were paid in other local industries, including coal-mining and the potteries.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] He built the largest cast iron structure of his era: the first cast-iron bridge ever built, as a crossing over the Severn near Coalbrookdale.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] The bridge made it possible for the village of Ironbridge to grow up around it, with the area being subsequently named Ironbridge Gorge.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] In 1776 Darby married Rebecca Smith of Doncaster, and they had seven children, of whom four survived to adulthood.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] He died in Madeley aged only 39 and was buried in the Quaker burial ground in Coalbrookdale.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] His sons Francis (1783–1850) and Richard (1788–1860) both worked in the Coalbrookdale Company.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] A secondary school in Telford, UK, is named after Abraham Darby III.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] The school's name is Abraham Darby Academy.
[src:cast-iron/abraham-darby-iii] In 1985 a rose cultivar Rosa 'Abraham Darby' bred by David C.H.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] All these mountains are part of the much larger Alpide belt.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The Alborz range is divided into the Western, Central, and Eastern Alborz Mountains.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The Western Alborz Range (usually called the Talysh) runs south-southeastward almost along the western coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The Central Alborz (the Alborz Mountains in the strictest sense) runs from west to east along the entire southern coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] In contrast, the Eastern Alborz Range runs in a northeasterly direction, toward the northern parts of the Khorasan region, southeast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Mount Damavand, the highest mountain in Iran, measuring 5,610.0 m (18,405.5 ft), is located in the Central Alborz Mountains.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Mount Damavand is the 12th most prominent peak in the world and the second most prominent in Asia after Mount Everest.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The name *Alborz* is derived from Harā Barazaitī, a legendary mountain in the Avesta, the main text of Zoroastrianism.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] *Harā Barazaitī* is from a Proto-Iranian name, *Harā Bṛzatī*, meaning "Mountain Rampart".
[src:cast-iron/alborz] *Bṛzatī* is the feminine form of the adjective *bṛzant-* "high", the ancestor of modern Persian *bouland* and *BarzBerazandeh*, cognate with Sanskrit *Brihat*.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] *Harā* may be interpreted as "watch" or "guard", from an Indo-European root **ser-* "protect".
[src:cast-iron/alborz] In Middle Persian, *Harā Barazaitī* became *Harborz*, Modern Persian *Alborz*, which is a cognate with Elbrus, the highest peak of the Caucasus.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Zoroastrians seem to identify the range with the dwelling place of the Peshyotan, and the Zoroastrian Ilm-e-Kshnoom sect identifies Mount Damavand as the home of the *Saheb-e-Dilan* ('Masters of the Heart').
[src:cast-iron/alborz] All these names reflect the same Iranian language compound, and have been speculatively identified, at one time or another, as the legendary mountain Hara Berezaiti of the Avesta.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The Alborz mountain range forms a barrier between the south Caspian and the Iranian plateau.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] It is only 60–130 km wide and consists of sedimentary series dating from Upper Devonian to Oligocene, prevalently Jurassic limestone over a granite core.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Continental conditions regarding sedimentation are reflected by thick Devonian sandstones and by Jurassic shales containing coal seams.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Marine conditions are reflected by Carboniferous and Permian strata that are composed mainly of limestones.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] In the Eastern Alborz Range, the far eastern section is formed by Mesozoic (chiefly Triassic and Jurassic) rocks, while the western part of the Eastern Alborz Range is made primarily of Paleozoic rocks.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Precambrian rocks can be found chiefly south of the city of Gorgan situated in the southeast of the Caspian Sea and, in much smaller amounts, in the central and western parts of the Central Alborz Range.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The central part of the Central Alborz Range is formed mainly of Triassic and Jurassic rocks, while the northwestern section of the range is mainly composed of Jurassic rocks.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Very thick beds of Tertiary (mostly Eocene) green volcanic tuffs and lavas are found mainly in the southwestern and south-central parts of the range.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] As the Tethys Sea was closed and the Arabian plate collided with the Iranian plate, and was pushed against it, and with the clockwise movement of the Eurasian plate towards the Iranian plate and their final collision, the Iranian plate was pressed from both sides.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The collisions finally caused the folding of the Upper Paleozoic, Mesozoic, and Paleogene rocks and the Cenozoic (chiefly the Eocene) volcanism, to form the Alborz Mountains, primarily during the Miocene.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] While the southern slopes of the Alborz Mountains are usually semiarid or arid, with irregular and low precipitation, the northern slopes of the range are usually humid, especially in the western parts of the Central Alborz.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The Alborz is the easternmost extent of many European plant species.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] In the southern slopes or the Elburz Range forest steppe ecoregion, the higher elevations are arid with few trees.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Juniper is the most common tree in inaccessible areas and at high elevation, while common shrubs are pistachio, maple, and almond.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] But in the northern slopes, the Caspian Hyrcanian mixed forests ecoregion is lush and forested.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The wild cypress is the dominant form of vegetation in some valleys, while olive trees grow in the western valleys of the Central Alborz near the Sefidrud.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The bezoar ibex, Blanford's fox, Rüppell's fox, red fox, Persian fallow deer, wild boar, Syrian brown bear, Persian leopard, Indian wolf, buzzard, geese, woodpecker, griffon vulture, and eagle are among important animals and birds found in the Alborz Mountains.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The extinct Caspian tiger also lived in the Alborz Mountains.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Archaeological evidence from Alborz indicates that early human groups have been present in the region since at least late Lower Paleolithic.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The Darband Cave located at the Gilan Province contains evidence for late Lower Paleolithic.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Stone artifacts and animal fossils were discovered by a group of archaeologists of the *Department of Paleolithic* of the National Museum of Iran and ICHTO of Gilan.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The presence of large numbers of cave bear and brown bear remains and sparse stone artifacts at the site indicates that Darband primarily represents a bear den.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] The co-occurrence of artifacts and bear bones does not imply human predation or scavenging.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Because there are no clear cut marks, except a few burning signs on the bear bones, they probably accumulated through natural processes.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] During Middle Paleolithic period, Neanderthals were most probably were present in the region as their fossil have been found at northwest of Alborz, in the Azykh Cave.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Their stone tools found in the Buzeir Cave and Kiaram cave and number of other surveyed sites.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Evidence for Modern human comes from a river side site called Garm Roud in the Mazandaran Province which dates back to about 30,000 years ago.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Due to the snowy winters of the Alborz Mountains, there are several ski resorts in different places across the range.
[src:cast-iron/alborz] Some of them, according to ski enthusiasts, are among the best in the world.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] At atmospheric pressure, three allotropic forms of iron exist, depending on temperature: alpha iron (α-Fe, ferrite), gamma iron (γ-Fe, austenite), and delta iron (δ-Fe, similar to alpha iron).
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] At very high pressure, a fourth form exists, epsilon iron (ε-Fe, hexaferrum).
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Some controversial experimental evidence suggests the existence of a fifth form that is stable at very high pressures and temperatures.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The phases of iron at atmospheric pressure are important because of the differences in solubility of carbon, forming different types of steel.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The high-pressure phases of iron are important as models for the solid parts of planetary cores.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The inner core of the Earth is generally assumed to consist essentially of a crystalline iron-nickel alloy with ε structure.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The outer core surrounding the solid inner core is believed to be composed of liquid iron mixed with nickel and trace amounts of lighter elements.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Below 912 °C (1,674 °F), iron has a body-centered cubic (bcc) crystal structure and is known as α-iron or **ferrite**.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] It is thermodynamically stable and a fairly soft metal. α-Fe can be subjected to pressures up to ca.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] 15 GPa before transforming into a high-pressure form termed ε-Fe, discussed below.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Magnetically, α-iron is paramagnetic at high temperatures.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] However, below its Curie temperature (*T*C or *A2*) of 771 °C (1044K or 1420 °F), it becomes ferromagnetic.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] In the past, the paramagnetic form of α-iron was known as *beta iron* (β-Fe).
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Even though the slight tetragonal distortion in the ferromagnetic state does constitute a true phase transition, the continuous nature of this transition results in only minor importance in steel heat treating.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The A2 line forms the boundary between the beta iron and alpha fields in the phase diagram in Figure 1.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Similarly, the A2 boundary is of only minor importance compared to the A1 (eutectoid), A3 and Acm critical temperatures.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The Acm, where austenite is in equilibrium with cementite + γ-Fe, is beyond the right edge in Fig.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The α + γ phase field is, technically, the β + γ field above the A2.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The beta designation maintains continuity of the Greek-letter progression of phases in iron and steel: α-Fe, β-Fe, austenite (γ-Fe), high-temperature δ-Fe, and high-pressure hexaferrum (ε-Fe).
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The primary phase of low-carbon or mild steel and most cast irons at room temperature is ferromagnetic α-Fe.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] It has a hardness of approximately 80 Brinell.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] When it dissolves in iron, carbon atoms occupy interstitial "holes".
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Being about twice the diameter of the tetrahedral hole, the carbon introduces a strong local strain field.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Mild steel (carbon steel with up to about 0.2 wt% C) consists mostly of α-Fe and increasing amounts of cementite (Fe3C, an iron carbide).
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The mixture adopts a lamellar structure called pearlite.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Since bainite and pearlite each contain α-Fe as a component, any iron-carbon alloy will contain some amount of α-Fe if it is allowed to reach equilibrium at room temperature.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The amount of α-Fe depends on the cooling process.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] β-Fe and the A2 critical temperature are important in induction heating of steel, such as for surface-hardening heat treatments.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Steel is typically austenitized at 900–1000 °C before it is quenched and tempered.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The high-frequency alternating magnetic field of induction heating heats the steel by two mechanisms below the Curie temperature: resistance or Joule heating and ferromagnetic hysteresis losses.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Above the A2 boundary, the hysteresis mechanism disappears and the required amount of energy per degree of temperature increase is thus substantially larger than below A2.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Load-matching circuits may be needed to vary the impedance in the induction power source to compensate for the change.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] When heating iron above 912 °C (1,674 °F), its crystal structure changes to a face-centered cubic (fcc) crystalline structure.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] In this form it is called gamma iron (γ-Fe) or austenite. γ-iron can dissolve considerably more carbon (as much as 2.04% by mass at 1,146 °C).
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] This γ form of carbon saturation is exhibited in austenitic stainless steel.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Peculiarly, above 1,394 °C (2,541 °F), iron changes back into the bcc structure, known as δ-Fe. δ-iron can dissolve as much as 0.08% of carbon by mass at 1,475 °C.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] It is stable up to its melting point of 1,538 °C (2,800 °F). δ-Fe cannot exist above 5.2 GPa, with austenite instead transitioning directly to a molten phase at these high pressures.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The triple point of hexaferrum, ferrite, and austenite is 10.5 GPa at 750 K.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Antiferromagnetism in alloys of epsilon-Fe with Mn, Os and Ru has been observed.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] An alternate stable form, if it exists, may appear at pressures of at least 50 GPa and temperatures of at least 1,500 K; it has been thought to have an orthorhombic or a double hcp structure.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] As of December 2011, recent and ongoing experiments are being conducted on high-pressure and superdense carbon allotropes.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The melting point of iron is experimentally well defined for pressures less than 50 GPa.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] For greater pressures, published data (as of 2007) put the γ-ε-liquid triple point at pressures that differ by tens of gigapascals and 1000 K in the melting point.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Generally speaking, molecular dynamics computer simulations of iron melting and shock wave experiments suggest higher melting points and a much steeper slope of the melting curve than static experiments carried out in diamond anvil cells.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] This same trend appears for ruthenium but not osmium.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The exact temperatures at which iron will transition from one crystal structure to another depends on how much and what type of other elements are dissolved in the iron.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] The phase boundary between the different solid phases is drawn on a binary phase diagram, usually plotted as temperature versus percent iron.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Adding some elements, such as Chromium, narrows the temperature range for the gamma phase, while others increase the temperature range of the gamma phase.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] In elements that reduce the gamma phase range, the alpha-gamma phase boundary connects with the gamma-delta phase boundary, forming what is usually called the *Gamma loop*.
[src:cast-iron/allotropes-of-iron] Adding Gamma loop additives keeps the iron in a body-centered cubic structure and prevents the steel from suffering phase transition to other solid states.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Alloy steels divide into two groups: low and high alloy.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The boundary between the two is disputed.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] William Smith and Javad Hashemi define the difference at 4.0%, while Paul Degarmo, *et al.*, define it at 8.0%.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The simplest steels are iron (Fe) alloyed with (0.1% to 1%) carbon (C) and nothing else (excepting slight impurities); these are called carbon steels.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] However, alloy steel encompasses steels with additional (metal) alloying elements.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Common alloyants include manganese (Mn) (the most common), nickel (Ni), chromium (Cr), molybdenum (Mo), vanadium (V), silicon (Si), and boron (B).
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Less common alloyants include Aluminium (Al), cobalt (Co), copper (Cu), cerium (Ce), niobium (Nb), titanium (Ti), tungsten (W), tin (Sn), zinc (Zn), lead (Pb), and zirconium (Zr).
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Alloy steels variously improve strength, hardness, toughness, wear resistance, corrosion resistance, hardenability, and hot hardness.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] To achieve these improved properties the metal may require specific heat treating, combined with strict cooling protocols.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Although alloy steels have been made for centuries, their metallurgy was not well understood until the advancing chemical science of the nineteenth century revealed their compositions.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Alloy steels from earlier times were expensive luxuries made on the model of "secret recipes" and forged into tools such as knives and swords.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Machine age alloy steels were tool steels and stainless steels.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Because of iron's ferromagnetic properties, some alloys find important applications where their responses to magnetism are valued, including in electric motors and in transformers.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Alloying elements enable specific properties.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] As a guideline, alloying elements are added in lower percentages (less than 5%) to increase strength or hardenability, or in larger percentages (over 5%) to improve corrosion resistance or temperature stability.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The alloying elements tend to form either solid solutions, compounds or carbides.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Alloying elements can have an effect on the eutectoid temperature.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The properties of steel depend on its microstructure: the arrangement of different phases, some harder, some with greater ductility.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] At the atomic level, the four phases of auto steel include martensite (the hardest yet most brittle), bainite (less hard), ferrite (more ductile), and austenite (the most ductile).
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The phases are arranged by steelmakers by manipulating intervals (sometimes by seconds only) and temperatures of the heating and cooling process.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Alloy steel pipes are widely used for transporting crude oil, natural gas, and petroleum products.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Their high strength and corrosion resistance make them ideal for high-pressure and high-temperature environments.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Other pipes are used in boilers, heat exchangers in thermal and nuclear power plants.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] They can withstand extreme temperatures and pressure conditions efficiently.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Alloy steel pipes are also used for safely handling corrosive chemicals and high-temperature fluids.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Their durability ensures long service life in harsh processing environments.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] They are furthermore used in structural applications such as bridges, buildings, and industrial frameworks.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Their strength and load-bearing capacity provide long-term reliability.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Alloy steel pipes are also used in manufacturing vehicle components and heavy machinery parts.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Their toughness and wear resistance support demanding mechanical operations.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The wide applications of alloy steel pipes across industries highlight their strength, durability, and reliability in demanding environments.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] From energy and infrastructure to manufacturing, the applications of alloy steel continue to support critical industrial operations.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] TRIP steels transform from relatively ductile to relatively hard under deformation such as in a car crash.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Deformation transforms austenitic microstructure to martensitic microstructure.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] TRIP steels use relatively high carbon content to create the austenitic microstructure.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Relatively high silicon/aluminum content suppresses carbide precipitation in the bainite region and helps accelerate ferrite/bainite formation.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] This helps retain carbon to support austenite at room temperature.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] A specific cooling process reduces the austenite/martensite transformation during forming.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] TRIP steels typically require an isothermal hold at an intermediate temperature during cooling, which produces some bainite.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The additional silicon/carbon requires weld cycle modification, such as the use of pulsating welding or dilution welding.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] In one approach steel is heated to a high temperature, cooled somewhat, held stable for an interval and then quenched.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] This produces islands of austenite surrounded by a matrix of softer ferrite, with regions of harder bainite and martensite.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The resulting product can absorb energy without fracturing, making it useful for auto parts such as bumpers and pillars.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Three generations of advanced, high-strength steel are available.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The first was created in the 1990s, increasing strength and ductility.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] A second generation used new alloys to further increase ductility, but were expensive and difficult to manufacture.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Refined heating and cooling patterns increase strength at some cost in ductility (vs 2nd generation).
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] These steels are claimed to approach nearly ten times the strength of earlier steels; and are much cheaper to manufacture.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] Researches created an alloy with the strength of steel and the lightness of titanium alloy.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] It combined iron, aluminum, carbon, manganese, and nickel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The other ingredient was uniformly distributed nanometer-sized B2 intermetallic (two metals with equal numbers of atoms) particles.
[src:cast-iron/alloy-steel] The use of nickel avoided problems with earlier attempts to use B2, while increasing ductility.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] An **alloy** is a mixture of chemical elements of which in most cases at least one is a metallic element, although it is also sometimes used for mixtures of elements; herein only **metallic alloys** are described.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Metallic alloys often have properties that differ from those of the pure elements from which they are made.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The vast majority of metals used for commercial purposes are alloyed to improve their properties or behavior, such as increased strength, hardness or corrosion resistance.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Metals may also be alloyed to reduce their overall cost, for instance alloys of gold and copper.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In an alloy, the atoms are joined by metallic bonding rather than by covalent bonds typically found in chemical compounds.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The alloy constituents are usually measured by mass percentage for practical applications, and in atomic fraction for basic science studies.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Alloys are usually classified as substitutional or interstitial alloys, depending on the atomic arrangement that forms the alloy.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] They can be further classified as homogeneous (consisting of a single phase), or heterogeneous (consisting of two or more phases) or intermetallic.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] An alloy may be a solid solution of metal elements (a single phase, where all metallic grains (crystals) are of the same composition) or a mixture of metallic phases (two or more solutions, forming a microstructure of different crystals within the metal).
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Examples of alloys include red gold (gold and copper), white gold (gold and silver), sterling silver (silver and copper), steel or silicon steel (iron with non-metallic carbon or silicon respectively), solder, brass, pewter, duralumin, bronze, and amalgams.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Alloys are used in a wide variety of applications, from the steel alloys used in everything from buildings to automobiles to surgical tools, to exotic titanium alloys used in the aerospace industry, to beryllium-copper alloys for non-sparking tools.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] An alloy is a mixture of chemical elements which forms an impure substance (admixture) that retains the characteristics of a metal.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Alloys are made by mixing two or more elements, at least one of which is a metal.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] This is usually called the primary metal or the base metal, and the name of this metal may also be the name of the alloy.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The other constituents may or may not be metals but, when mixed with the molten base, they will be soluble and dissolve into the mixture.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The mechanical properties of alloys will often be quite different from those of its individual constituents.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] A metal that is normally very soft (malleable), such as aluminium, can be altered by alloying it with another soft metal, such as copper.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Although both metals are very soft and ductile, the resulting aluminium–copper alloy will have much greater strength.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Adding a small amount of non-metallic carbon to iron trades its great ductility for the greater strength of an alloy called steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Due to its very-high strength, but still substantial toughness, and its ability to be greatly altered by heat treatment, steel is one of the most useful and common alloys in modern use.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] By adding chromium to steel, its resistance to corrosion can be enhanced, creating stainless steel, while adding silicon will alter its electrical characteristics, producing silicon steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Like oil and water, a molten metal may not always be miscible with another element.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] For example, lithium, magnesium, or silver are almost completely insoluble with pure iron.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Even when the constituents are soluble, each will usually have a saturation point, beyond which no more of the constituent can be added.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Iron, for example, can stably hold a maximum of 6.67% carbon, forming a compound called cementite.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Although the elements of an alloy usually must be soluble in the liquid state, they may not always be soluble in the solid state.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] If the metals remain soluble when solid, the alloy forms a solid solution, becoming a homogeneous structure consisting of identical crystals, called a phase.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] If as the mixture cools the constituents become insoluble, they may separate to form two or more different types of crystals, creating a heterogeneous microstructure of different phases, some with more of one constituent than the other.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, in other alloys, the insoluble elements may not separate until after crystallization occurs.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] If cooled very quickly, they first crystallize as a homogeneous phase, but they are supersaturated with the secondary constituents.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] As time passes, the atoms of these supersaturated alloys can separate from the crystal lattice, becoming more stable, and forming a second phase that serves to reinforce the crystals internally.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Some alloys, such as electrum—an alloy of silver and gold—occur naturally.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Meteorites are sometimes made of naturally occurring alloys of iron and nickel, but are not native to the Earth.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] One of the first alloys made by humans was bronze, which is a mixture of the metals tin and copper.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Bronze was an extremely useful alloy to the ancients, because it is much stronger and harder than either of its components.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, in ancient times, it could only be created as an accidental byproduct from the heating of iron ore in fires (smelting) during the manufacture of iron.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Other ancient alloys include pewter, brass, and pig iron.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In the modern age, steel can be created in many forms.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Carbon steel can be made by varying only the carbon content, producing soft alloys like mild steel or hard alloys like spring steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Alloy steels can be made by adding other elements, such as chromium, molybdenum, vanadium, or nickel, resulting in alloys such as high-speed steel or tool steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Small amounts of manganese are usually alloyed with most modern steels because of its ability to remove unwanted impurities, like phosphorus, sulfur, and oxygen, which can have detrimental effects on the alloy.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, most alloys were not created until the 1900s, such as various aluminium, titanium, nickel, and magnesium alloys.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Some modern superalloys, such as incoloy, inconel, and hastelloy, may consist of a multitude of different elements.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] An alloy is technically an impure metal, but when referring to alloys, the term *impurities* usually denotes undesirable elements.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Such impurities are introduced from the base metals and alloying elements, but are removed during processing.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] For instance, sulfur is a common impurity in steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Sulfur combines readily with iron to form iron sulfide, which is very brittle, creating weak spots in the steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Lithium, sodium and calcium are common impurities in aluminium alloys, which can have adverse effects on the structural integrity of castings.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Conversely, otherwise pure-metals that contain unwanted impurities are often called "impure metals" and are not usually referred to as alloys.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Impure metals such as cast iron or wrought iron are less controlled, but are often considered useful.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Oxygen, present in the air, readily combines with most metals to form metal oxides, especially at higher temperatures encountered during alloying.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Depending on the alloy, this can eventually result in a failure of the component being produced.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Great care is often taken during the alloying process to remove excess impurities, using fluxes, chemical additives, or other methods of extractive metallurgy.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Alloying a metal is done by combining it with one or more other elements.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The most common and oldest alloying process is performed by heating the base metal beyond its melting point and then dissolving the solutes into the molten liquid, which may be possible even if the melting point of the solute is far greater than that of the base.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] For example, in its liquid state, titanium is a very strong solvent capable of dissolving most metals and elements.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In addition, it readily absorbs gases like oxygen and burns in the presence of nitrogen.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] This increases the chance of contamination from any contacting surface, and so must be melted in vacuum induction-heating and special, water-cooled, copper crucibles.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Carbon has a very high melting-point and only does so under high atmospheric pressure, so it was impossible for ancient civilizations to combine with iron as a liquid solute.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] It may also be done with one, more, or all of the constituents in the solid state, such as found in ancient methods of pattern welding (solid-solid), shear steel (solid-solid), or crucible steel production (solid-liquid), mixing the elements via solid-state diffusion.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] By adding another element to a metal, differences in the size of the atoms create internal stresses in the lattice of the metallic crystals; stresses that often enhance its properties.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] For example, the combination of carbon with wrought iron produces steel, which is stronger than iron, its primary element.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The electrical and thermal conductivity of alloys is usually lower than that of the pure metals.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The physical properties, such as density, reactivity, Young's modulus of an alloy may not differ greatly from those of its base element, but engineering properties such as tensile strength, ductility, and shear strength may be substantially different from those of the constituent materials.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] This is sometimes a result of the sizes of the atoms in the alloy, because larger atoms exert a compressive force on neighboring atoms, and smaller atoms exert a tensile force on their neighbors, helping the alloy resist deformation.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Sometimes alloys may exhibit marked differences in behavior even when small amounts of one element are present.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] For example, impurities in semiconducting ferromagnetic alloys lead to different properties, as first predicted by White, Hogan, Suhl, Tian Abrie and Nakamura.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Unlike pure metals, most alloys do not have a single melting point, but a melting range during which the material is a mixture of solid and liquid phases (a slush).
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The temperature at which melting begins is called the solidus, and the temperature when melting is just complete is called the liquidus.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] For many alloys there is a particular alloy proportion (in some cases more than one), called either a eutectic mixture or a peritectic composition, which gives the alloy a unique and low melting point, and no liquid/solid slush transition.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Alloying elements are added to a base metal, to induce hardness, toughness, ductility, or other desired properties.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Many metals and alloys can be work hardened by creating defects in their crystal structure.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] These defects are created during plastic deformation by hammering, bending, extruding, et cetera, and are permanent unless the metal is recrystallized.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Otherwise, some alloys can also have their properties altered by heat treatment.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Nearly all metals can be softened by annealing, which recrystallizes the alloy and repairs the defects, but not as many can be hardened by controlled heating and cooling.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Many alloys of aluminium, copper, magnesium, titanium, and nickel can be strengthened to some degree by some method of heat treatment, but few respond to this to the same degree as does steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The base metal iron of the iron-carbon alloy known as steel, undergoes a change in the arrangement (allotropy) of the atoms of its crystal matrix at a certain temperature (usually 820 °C (1,500 °F) or more, depending on carbon content).
[src:cast-iron/alloy] This allows the smaller carbon atoms to enter the interstices of the iron crystal.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] When this diffusion happens, the carbon atoms are said to be in *solution* in the iron, forming a particular single, homogeneous, crystalline phase called austenite.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] If the steel is cooled slowly, the carbon can diffuse out of the iron and it will gradually revert to its low temperature allotrope.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] During slow cooling, the carbon atoms will no longer be as soluble with the iron, and will be forced to precipitate out of solution, nucleating into a more concentrated form of iron carbide (Fe3C) in the spaces between the pure iron crystals.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The steel then becomes heterogeneous, as it is formed of two phases, the iron-carbon phase called cementite (or carbide), and pure iron ferrite.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Such a heat treatment produces a steel that is rather soft.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] If the steel is cooled quickly, however, the carbon atoms will not have time to diffuse and precipitate out as carbide, but will be trapped within the iron crystals.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] When rapidly cooled, a diffusionless (martensite) transformation occurs, in which the carbon atoms become trapped in solution.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] This causes the iron crystals to deform as the crystal structure tries to change to its low temperature state, leaving those crystals very hard but much less ductile (more brittle).
[src:cast-iron/alloy] While the high strength of steel results when diffusion and precipitation is prevented (forming martensite), most heat-treatable alloys are precipitation hardening alloys, that depend on the diffusion of alloying elements to achieve their strength.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] When heated to form a solution and then cooled quickly, these alloys become much softer than normal, during the diffusionless transformation, but then harden as they age.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The solutes in these alloys will precipitate over time, forming intermetallic phases, which are difficult to discern from the base metal.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Unlike steel, in which the solid solution separates into different crystal phases (carbide and ferrite), precipitation hardening alloys form different phases within the same crystal.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] These intermetallic alloys appear homogeneous in crystal structure, but tend to behave heterogeneously, becoming hard and somewhat brittle.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In 1906, precipitation hardening alloys were discovered by Alfred Wilm.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Precipitation hardening alloys, such as certain alloys of aluminium, titanium, and copper, are heat-treatable alloys that soften when quenched (cooled quickly), and then harden over time.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Wilm had been searching for a way to harden aluminium alloys for use in machine-gun cartridge cases.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Knowing that aluminium-copper alloys were heat-treatable to some degree, Wilm tried quenching a ternary alloy of aluminium, copper, and the addition of magnesium, but was initially disappointed with the results.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, when Wilm retested it the next day he discovered that the alloy increased in hardness when left to age at room temperature, and far exceeded his expectations.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Although an explanation for the phenomenon was not provided until 1919, duralumin was one of the first "age hardening" alloys used, becoming the primary building material for the first Zeppelins, and was soon followed by many others.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Because they often exhibit a combination of high strength and low weight, these alloys became widely used in many forms of industry, including the construction of modern aircraft.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] When a molten metal is mixed with another substance, there are two mechanisms that can cause an alloy to form, called *atom exchange* and the *interstitial mechanism*.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The relative size of each element in the mix plays a primary role in determining which mechanism will occur.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] When the atoms are relatively similar in size, the atom exchange method usually happens, where some of the atoms composing the metallic crystals are substituted with atoms of the other constituent.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] This is called a *substitutional alloy*.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Examples of substitutional alloys include bronze and brass, in which some of the copper atoms are substituted with either tin or zinc atoms respectively.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In the case of the interstitial mechanism, one atom is usually much smaller than the other and can not successfully substitute for the other type of atom in the crystals of the base metal.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Instead, the smaller atoms become trapped in the interstitial sites between the atoms of the crystal matrix.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] This is referred to as an *interstitial alloy*.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Steel is an example of an interstitial alloy, because the very small carbon atoms fit into interstices of the iron matrix.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Stainless steel is an example of a combination of interstitial and substitutional alloys, because the carbon atoms fit into the interstices, but some of the iron atoms are substituted by nickel and chromium atoms.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The use of alloys by humans started with the use of meteoric iron, a naturally occurring alloy of nickel and iron.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] It is the main constituent of iron meteorites.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] As no metallurgic processes were used to separate iron from nickel, the alloy was used as it was.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Meteoric iron could be forged from a red heat to make objects such as tools, weapons, and nails.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In many cultures it was shaped by cold hammering into knives and arrowheads.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Meteoric iron was very rare and valuable, and difficult for ancient people to work.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Iron is usually found as iron ore on Earth, except for one deposit of native iron in Greenland, which was used by the Inuit.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Native copper, however, was found worldwide, along with silver, gold, and platinum, which were also used to make tools, jewelry, and other objects since Neolithic times.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Copper was the hardest of these metals, and the most widely distributed.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] It became one of the most important metals to the ancients.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Starting around 10,000 years ago in the highlands of Anatolia (Turkey), humans learned to smelt metals such as copper and tin from ore.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Early bronze alloys used copper and arsenic, but the latter can be toxic to the metal-workers.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Around 2500 BC, people began alloying tin and copper to form bronze, which was much harder than its ingredients.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, tin was rare, being found mostly in Great Britain.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In the Middle East, people began alloying copper with zinc to form brass.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Ancient civilizations took into account the mixture and the various properties it produced, such as hardness, toughness and melting point, under various conditions of temperature and work hardening, developing much of the information contained in modern alloy phase diagrams.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] For example, arrowheads from the Chinese Qin dynasty (around 200 BC) were often constructed with a hard bronze-head, but a softer bronze-tang, combining the alloys to prevent both dulling and breaking during use.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Mercury has been smelted from cinnabar for thousands of years.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Mercury dissolves many metals, such as gold, silver, and tin, to form amalgams (an alloy in a soft paste or liquid form at ambient temperature).
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Amalgams have been used since 200 BC in China for gilding objects such as armor and mirrors with precious metals.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The ancient Romans often used mercury-tin amalgams for gilding their armor.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The amalgam was applied as a paste and then heated until the mercury vaporized, leaving the gold, silver, or tin behind.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Mercury was often used in mining, to extract precious metals like gold and silver from their ores.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Many ancient civilizations alloyed metals for purely aesthetic purposes.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In ancient Egypt and Mycenae, gold was often alloyed with copper to produce red-gold, or iron to produce a bright burgundy-gold.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Gold was often found alloyed with silver or other metals to produce various types of colored gold.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] These metals were also used to strengthen each other, for more practical purposes.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Copper was often added to silver to make sterling silver, increasing its strength for use in dishes, silverware, and other practical items.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Quite often, precious metals were alloyed with less valuable substances as a means to deceive buyers.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Around 250 BC, Archimedes was commissioned by the King of Syracuse to find a way to check the purity of the gold in a crown, leading to the famous bath-house shouting of "Eureka!" upon the discovery of Archimedes' principle.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The term pewter covers a variety of alloys consisting primarily of tin.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] As a pure metal, tin is much too soft to use for most practical purposes.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, during the Bronze Age, tin was a rare metal in many parts of Europe and the Mediterranean, so it was often valued higher than gold.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] To make jewellery, cutlery, or other objects from tin, workers usually alloyed it with other metals to increase strength and hardness.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] These metals were typically lead, antimony, bismuth or copper.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] These solutes were sometimes added individually in varying amounts, or added together, making a wide variety of objects, ranging from practical items such as dishes, surgical tools, candlesticks or funnels, to decorative items like ear rings and hair clips.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The earliest examples of pewter come from ancient Egypt, around 1450 BC.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The use of pewter was widespread across Europe, from France to Norway and Britain (where most of the ancient tin was mined) to the Near East.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The alloy was also used in China and the Far East, arriving in Japan around 800 AD, where it was used for making objects like ceremonial vessels, tea canisters, or chalices used in shinto shrines.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The first known smelting of iron began in Anatolia, around 1800 BC.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Called the bloomery process, it produced very soft but ductile wrought iron.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] By 800 BC, iron-making technology had spread to Europe, arriving in Japan around 700 AD.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Pig iron, a very hard but brittle alloy of iron and carbon, was being produced in China as early as 1200 BC, but did not arrive in Europe until the Middle Ages.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Pig iron has a lower melting point than iron, and was used for making cast iron.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, these metals found little practical use until the introduction of crucible steel around 300 BC.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] These steels were of poor quality, and the introduction of pattern welding, around the 1st century AD, sought to balance the extreme properties of the alloys by laminating them, to create a tougher metal.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Around 700 AD, the Japanese began folding bloomery-steel and cast iron in alternating layers to increase the strength of their swords, using clay fluxes to remove slag and impurities.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] This method of Japanese swordsmithing produced one of the purest steel-alloys of the ancient world.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] While the use of iron started to become more widespread around 1200 BC, mainly because of interruptions in the trade routes for tin, the metal was much softer than bronze.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, very small amounts of steel, (an alloy of iron and around 1% carbon), was always a byproduct of the bloomery process.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The ability to modify the hardness of steel by heat treatment had been known since 1100 BC, and the rare material was valued for the manufacture of tools and weapons.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Because the ancients could not produce temperatures high enough to melt iron fully, the production of steel in decent quantities did not occur until the introduction of blister steel during the Middle Ages.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] This method introduced carbon by heating wrought iron in charcoal for long periods of time, but the absorption of carbon in this manner is extremely slow thus the penetration was not very deep, so the alloy was not homogeneous.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In 1740, Benjamin Huntsman began melting blister steel in a crucible to even out the carbon content, creating the first process for the mass production of tool steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Huntsman's process was used for manufacturing tool steel until the early 1900s.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The introduction of the blast furnace to Europe in the Middle Ages meant that people could produce pig iron in much higher volumes than wrought iron.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Because pig iron could be melted, people began to develop processes to reduce carbon in liquid pig iron to create steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Puddling had been used in China since the first century, and was introduced in Europe during the 1700s, where molten pig iron was stirred while exposed to the air, to remove the carbon by oxidation.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In 1858, Henry Bessemer developed a process of steel-making by blowing hot air through liquid pig iron to reduce the carbon content.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The Bessemer process led to the first large scale manufacture of steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Steel is an alloy of iron and carbon, but the term *alloy steel* usually only refers to steels that contain other elements— like vanadium, molybdenum, or cobalt—in amounts sufficient to alter the properties of the base steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Since ancient times, when steel was used primarily for tools and weapons, the methods of producing and working the metal were often closely guarded secrets.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Even long after the Age of Enlightenment, the steel industry was very competitive and manufacturers went through great lengths to keep their processes confidential, resisting any attempts to scientifically analyze the material for fear it would reveal their methods.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] For example, the people of Sheffield, a center of steel production in England, were known to routinely bar visitors and tourists from entering town to deter industrial espionage.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Thus, almost no metallurgical information existed about steel until 1860.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Afterward, many people began experimenting with various alloys of steel without much success.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, in 1882, Robert Hadfield, being a pioneer in steel metallurgy, took an interest and produced a steel alloy containing around 12% manganese.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Called mangalloy, it exhibited extreme hardness and toughness, becoming the first commercially viable alloy-steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Afterward, he created silicon steel, launching the search for other possible alloys of steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Robert Forester Mushet found that by adding tungsten to steel it could produce a very hard edge that would resist losing its hardness at high temperatures.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Mushet's special steel" (RMS) became the first high-speed steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Mushet's steel was quickly replaced by tungsten carbide steel, developed by Taylor and White in 1900, in which they doubled the tungsten content and added small amounts of chromium and vanadium, producing a superior steel for use in lathes and machining tools.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In 1903, the Wright brothers used a chromium-nickel steel to make the crankshaft for their airplane engine, while in 1908 Henry Ford began using vanadium steels for parts like crankshafts and valves in his Model T Ford, due to their higher strength and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In 1912, the Krupp Ironworks in Germany developed a rust-resistant steel by adding 21% chromium and 7% nickel, producing the first stainless steel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] A typical example of a modern alloy is 304 grade stainless steel which is commonly used for kitchen utensils, pans, knives and forks.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Sometime also known as 18/8, it as an alloy consisting broadly of 74% iron, 18% chromium and 8% nickel.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The chromium and nickel alloying elements add strength and hardness to the majority iron element, but their main function is to make it resistant to rust/corrosion.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Due to their high reactivity, most metals were not discovered until the 19th century.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] A method for extracting aluminium from bauxite was proposed by Humphry Davy in 1807, using an electric arc.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Although his attempts were unsuccessful, by 1855 the first sales of pure aluminium reached the market.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, as extractive metallurgy was still in its infancy, most aluminium extraction-processes produced unintended alloys contaminated with other elements found in the ore; the most abundant of which was copper.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] These aluminium-copper alloys (at the time termed "aluminium bronze") preceded pure aluminium, offering greater strength and hardness over the soft, pure metal, and to a slight degree were found to be heat treatable.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] However, due to their softness and limited hardenability these alloys found little practical use, and were more of a novelty, until the Wright brothers used an aluminium alloy to construct the first airplane engine in 1903.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] During the time between 1865 and 1910, processes for extracting many other metals were discovered, such as chromium, vanadium, tungsten, iridium, cobalt, and molybdenum, and various alloys were developed.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] Prior to 1910, research mainly consisted of private individuals tinkering in their own laboratories.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] The Doehler Die Casting Co. of Toledo, Ohio were known for the production of *Brastil*, a high tensile corrosion resistant bronze alloy.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] As a part of industrial procurement for the production of precision alloys, intermediate good 'master alloy' ingots or powder are produced with a consistent mixture of desired metal content.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] These master alloys can then be combined to produce the final desired alloy for production.
[src:cast-iron/alloy] In the aluminium alloy industry, master alloy is commonly introduced to aluminium to adjust the metal grain of the final alloy.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:cast-iron/astm-international] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Carbon (C), ranging from 1.8 to 4% by weight, and silicon (Si), 1–3% by weight, are the main alloying elements of cast iron.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Iron alloys with lower carbon content are known as steel.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron tends to be brittle, except for malleable cast irons.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Some alloys are resistant to damage by oxidation.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] In general, cast iron is notoriously difficult to weld.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The earliest cast-iron artifacts date to the 8th century BC, and were discovered by archaeologists in what is now Jiangsu, China.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron was used in ancient China to mass-produce weaponry for warfare, as well as agriculture and architecture.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] During the 15th century AD, cast iron was utilized for cannons and shot in Burgundy, France, and in England during the Reformation.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The amounts of cast iron used for cannons required large-scale production.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The first cast-iron bridge was built during the 1770s by Abraham Darby III, and is known as the Iron Bridge in Shropshire, England.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron was also used in the construction of buildings.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron is made from pig iron, which is the product of melting iron ore in a blast furnace.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron can be made directly from the molten pig iron or by re-melting pig iron, often along with substantial quantities of iron, steel, limestone, carbon (coke) and taking various steps to remove undesirable contaminants.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Phosphorus and sulfur may be burnt out of the molten iron, but this also burns out the carbon, which must be replaced.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Depending on the application, carbon and silicon content are adjusted to the desired levels, which may be anywhere from 2–3.5% and 1–3%, respectively.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] If desired, other elements are then added to the melt before the final form is produced by casting.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron is sometimes melted in a special type of blast furnace known as a cupola, but in modern applications, it is more often melted in electric induction furnaces or electric arc furnaces.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] After melting is complete, the molten cast iron is poured into a holding furnace or ladle.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron's properties are changed by adding various alloying elements, or alloyants.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Next to carbon, silicon is the most important alloyant because it forces carbon out of solution.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] A low percentage of silicon allows carbon to remain in solution, forming iron carbide and producing white cast iron.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] A high percentage of silicon forces carbon out of solution, forming graphite and producing grey cast iron.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Other alloying agents, manganese, chromium, molybdenum, titanium, and vanadium counteract silicon, and promote the retention of carbon and the formation of those carbides.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Nickel and copper increase strength and machinability, but do not change the amount of graphite formed.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Carbon as graphite produces a softer iron, reduces shrinkage, lowers strength, and decreases density.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Sulfur, largely a contaminant when present, forms iron sulfide, which prevents the formation of graphite and increases hardness.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Sulfur makes molten cast iron viscous, which causes defects.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] To counter the effects of sulfur, manganese is added, because the two form into manganese sulfide instead of iron sulfide.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The manganese sulfide is lighter than the melt, so it tends to float out of the melt and into the slag.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The amount of manganese required to neutralize sulfur is 1.7 × sulfur content + 0.3%.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] If more than this amount of manganese is added, then manganese carbide forms, which increases hardness and chilling, except in grey iron, where up to 1% of manganese increases strength and density.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Nickel is one of the most common alloying elements, because it refines the pearlite and graphite structures, improves toughness, and evens out hardness differences between section thicknesses.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Chromium is added in small amounts to reduce free graphite, produce chill, and because it is a powerful carbide stabilizer; nickel is often added in conjunction.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] A small amount of tin can be added as a substitute for 0.5% chromium.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Copper is added in the ladle or in the furnace, on the order of 0.5–2.5%, to decrease chill, refine graphite, and increase fluidity.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Molybdenum is added on the order of 0.3–1% to increase chill and refine the graphite and pearlite structure; it is often added in conjunction with nickel, copper, and chromium to form high strength irons.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Titanium is added as a degasser and deoxidizer, but it also increases fluidity.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Vanadium at 0.15–0.5% is added to cast iron to stabilize cementite, increase hardness, and increase resistance to wear and heat.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Zirconium at 0.1–0.3% helps to form graphite, deoxidize, and increase fluidity.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] In malleable iron melts, bismuth is added at 0.002–0.01% to increase how much silicon can be added.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] In white iron, boron is added to aid in the production of malleable iron; it also reduces the coarsening effect of bismuth.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Grey cast iron is characterised by its graphitic microstructure, which causes fractures of the material to have a grey appearance.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] It is the most commonly used cast iron and the most widely used cast material based on weight.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Most cast irons have a chemical composition of 2.5–4.0% carbon, 1–3% silicon, and the remainder iron.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Grey cast iron has less tensile strength and shock resistance than steel, but its compressive strength is comparable to low- and medium-carbon steel.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] These mechanical properties are controlled by the size and shape of the graphite flakes present in the microstructure and can be characterised according to the guidelines given by the ASTM.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The tribological behavior of structural alloys during sliding friction is strongly influenced by microstructure and phase composition.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Austenitic manganese steels and manganese cast irons exhibit complex wear mechanisms associated with strain hardening, plastic deformation of the surface layer and the formation of wear debris during friction.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Such materials may develop hardened surface layers during sliding contact, which significantly influences wear resistance and friction stability.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] White cast iron displays white fractured surfaces due to the presence of an iron carbide precipitate called cementite.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] With a lower silicon content (graphitizing agent) and faster cooling rate, the carbon in white cast iron precipitates out of the melt as the metastable phase cementite, Fe3C, rather than graphite.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The cementite which precipitates from the melt forms as relatively large particles.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] As the iron carbide precipitates out, it withdraws carbon from the original melt, moving the mixture toward one that is closer to eutectic, and the remaining phase is the lower iron-carbon austenite (which on cooling might transform to martensite).
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] These eutectic carbides are much too large to provide the benefit of what is called precipitation hardening (as in some steels, where much smaller cementite precipitates might inhibit plastic deformation by impeding the movement of dislocations through the pure iron ferrite matrix).
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Rather, they increase the bulk hardness of the cast iron simply by virtue of their own very high hardness and their substantial volume fraction, such that the bulk hardness can be approximated by a rule of mixtures.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] In any case, they offer hardness at the expense of toughness.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Since carbide makes up a large fraction of the material, white cast iron could reasonably be classified as a cermet.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] It is difficult to cool thick castings fast enough to solidify the melt as white cast iron all the way through.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] However, rapid cooling can be used to solidify a shell of white cast iron, after which the remainder cools more slowly to form a core of grey cast iron.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The resulting casting, called a *chilled casting*, has the benefits of a hard surface with a somewhat tougher interior.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] High-chromium white iron alloys allow massive castings (for example, a 10-tonne impeller) to be sand cast, as the chromium reduces cooling rate required to produce carbides through the greater thicknesses of material.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Chromium also produces carbides with impressive abrasion resistance.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] These high-chromium alloys attribute their superior hardness to the presence of chromium carbides.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The main form of these carbides are the eutectic or primary M7C3 carbides, where "M" represents iron or chromium and can vary depending on the alloy's composition.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The eutectic carbides form as bundles of hollow hexagonal rods and grow perpendicular to the hexagonal basal plane.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The hardness of these carbides are within the range of 1500-1800HV.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Malleable iron starts as a white iron casting that is then heat treated for a day or two at about 950 °C (1,740 °F) and then cooled over a day or two.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] As a result, the carbon in iron carbide transforms into graphite and ferrite plus carbon.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The slow process allows the surface tension to form the graphite into spheroidal particles rather than flakes.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Due to their lower aspect ratio, the spheroids are relatively short and far from one another, and have a lower cross section vis-a-vis a propagating crack or phonon.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] They also have blunt boundaries, as opposed to flakes, which alleviates the stress concentration problems found in grey cast iron.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] In general, the properties of malleable cast iron are more like those of mild steel.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] There is a limit to how large a part can be cast in malleable iron, as it is made from white cast iron.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Developed in 1948, ***nodular*** or *ductile cast iron* has its graphite in the form of very tiny nodules with the graphite in the form of concentric layers forming the nodules.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] As a result, the properties of ductile cast iron are that of a spongy steel without the stress concentration effects that flakes of graphite would produce.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The carbon percentage present is 3–4% and percentage of silicon is 1.8–2.8%.Tiny amounts of 0.02 to 0.1% magnesium, and only 0.02 to 0.04% cerium added to these alloys slow the growth of graphite precipitates by bonding to the edges of the graphite planes.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Along with careful control of other elements and timing, this allows the carbon to separate as spheroidal particles as the material solidifies.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The properties are similar to malleable iron, but parts can be cast with larger sections.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron and wrought iron can be produced unintentionally when smelting copper using iron ore as a flux.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The earliest cast-iron artifacts date to the 8th century BC, and were discovered by archaeologists in what is now modern Luhe County, Jiangsu in China during the Warring States period.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] This is based on an analysis of the artifact's microstructures.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron can be poured into a mold to create complex shapes that would be difficult or impossible to make with other traditional metalworking techniques.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] However, because cast iron is comparatively brittle, it is not suitable for purposes where a sharp edge or flexibility is required.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] It is strong under compression, but not under tension.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron was invented in China in the 8th century BC and poured into molds to make ploughshares and pots as well as weapons and pagodas.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Although steel was more desirable, cast iron was cheaper and thus was more commonly used for implements in ancient China, while wrought iron or steel was used for weapons.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The Chinese developed a method of annealing cast iron by keeping hot castings in an oxidizing atmosphere for a week or longer in order to burn off some carbon near the surface in order to keep the surface layer from being too brittle.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Compared to earlier bloomery iron, China's development of a high-temperature cast iron system significantly increased iron production and supply capacity.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Combined with subsequent decarburization and forging processes, this enabled ironware to be both mass-produced and practical, thereby improving overall productivity in agriculture, military, and engineering.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The technology of cast iron was transferred to the West from China.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Al-Qazvini in the 13th century and other travellers subsequently noted an iron industry in the Alburz Mountains to the south of the Caspian Sea.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] This is close to the silk route, thus the use of cast-iron technology being derived from China is conceivable.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Upon its introduction to the West in the 15th century it was used for cannon and shot.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Henry VIII (reigned 1509–1547) initiated the casting of cannon in England.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Soon, English iron workers using blast furnaces developed the technique of producing cast-iron cannons, which, while heavier than the prevailing bronze cannons, were much cheaper and enabled England to arm its navy better.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast-iron pots were made at many English blast furnaces at the time.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] In 1707, Abraham Darby patented a new method of making pots (and kettles) thinner and hence cheaper than those made by traditional methods.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] This meant that his Coalbrookdale furnaces became dominant as suppliers of pots, an activity in which they were joined in the 1720s and 1730s by a small number of other coke-fired blast furnaces.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Application of the steam engine to power blast bellows (indirectly by pumping water to a waterwheel) in Britain, beginning in 1743 and increasing in the 1750s, was a key factor in increasing the production of cast iron, which surged in the following decades.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] In addition to overcoming the limitation on water power, the steam-pumped-water powered blast gave higher furnace temperatures which allowed the use of higher lime ratios, enabling the conversion from charcoal (supplies of wood for which were inadequate) to coke.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The ironmasters of the Weald continued producing cast irons until the 1760s, and armament was one of the main uses of irons after the Restoration.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The use of cast iron for structural purposes began in the late 1770s, when Abraham Darby III built The Iron Bridge, although short beams had already been used, such as in the blast furnaces at Coalbrookdale.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Other inventions followed, including one patented by Thomas Paine.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast-iron bridges became commonplace as the Industrial Revolution gathered pace.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Thomas Telford adopted the material for his bridge upstream at Buildwas, and then for Longdon-on-Tern Aqueduct, a canal trough aqueduct at Longdon-on-Tern on the Shrewsbury Canal.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] It was followed by the Chirk Aqueduct and the Pontcysyllte Aqueduct, both of which remain in use following the recent restorations.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The best way of using cast iron for bridge construction was by using arches, so that all the material is in compression.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron, again like masonry, is very strong in compression.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Wrought iron, like most other kinds of iron and indeed like most metals in general, is strong in tension, and also tough – resistant to fracturing.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The relationship between wrought iron and cast iron, for structural purposes, may be thought of as analogous to the relationship between wood and stone.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The Dee bridge disaster was caused by excessive loading at the centre of the beam by a passing train, and many similar bridges had to be demolished and rebuilt, often in wrought iron.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The bridge had been badly designed, being trussed with wrought iron straps, which were wrongly thought to reinforce the structure.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The centres of the beams were put into bending, with the lower edge in tension, where cast iron, like masonry, is very weak.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Nevertheless, cast iron continued to be used in inappropriate structural ways, until the Tay Rail Bridge disaster of 1879 cast serious doubt on the use of the material.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Crucial lugs for holding tie bars and struts in the Tay Bridge had been cast integral with the columns, and they failed in the early stages of the accident.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] In addition, the bolt holes were also cast and not drilled.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Thus, because of casting's draft angle, the tension from the tie bars was placed on the hole's edge rather than being spread over the length of the hole.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The replacement bridge was built in wrought iron and steel.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Further bridge collapses occurred, however, culminating in the Norwood Junction rail accident of 1891.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Thousands of cast-iron rail underbridges were eventually replaced by steel equivalents by 1900 owing to the widespread concern about cast iron under bridges on the rail network in Britain.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast-iron columns, pioneered in mill buildings, enabled architects to build multi-storey buildings without the enormously thick walls required for masonry buildings of any height.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] They also opened up floor spaces in factories, and sight lines in churches and auditoriums.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] By the mid 19th century, cast iron columns were common in warehouse and industrial buildings, combined with wrought or cast iron beams, eventually leading to the development of steel-framed skyscrapers.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron was also used sometimes for decorative facades, especially in the United States, and the Soho district of New York has numerous examples.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] It was also used occasionally for complete prefabricated buildings, such as the historic Iron Building in Watervliet, New York.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Another important use was in textile mills.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The air in the mills contained flammable fibres from the cotton, hemp, or wool being spun.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] As a result, textile mills had an alarming propensity to burn down.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The solution was to build them completely of non-combustible materials, and it was found convenient to provide the building with an iron frame, largely of cast iron, replacing flammable wood.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] The first such building was at Ditherington in Shrewsbury, Shropshire.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Many other warehouses were built using cast-iron columns and beams, although faulty designs, flawed beams or overloading sometimes caused building collapses and structural failures.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] During the Industrial Revolution, cast iron was also widely used for frame and other fixed parts of machinery, including spinning and later weaving machines in textile mills.
[src:cast-iron/cast-iron] Cast iron became widely used, and many towns had foundries producing industrial and agricultural machinery.
